{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584411","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584411"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:46:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:46:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14517"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14517","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14517"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.85,0.03,0,0.04,0.09]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7212"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56516"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7212","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7212"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14517"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"42068"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4899"},{"type":"tags","id":"4900"},{"type":"tags","id":"4914"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4941"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"17503"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17504"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"56516","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/56516"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following body regions receives its primary blood supply from the subclavian arteries?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Upper limbs","Lower limbs","Abdomen","Head","Neck"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eupper limbs\u003C/strong\u003E receive their primary blood supply from the subclavian arteries. These arteries branch off from the aortic arch (left subclavian artery) and the brachiocephalic trunk (right subclavian artery). As they enter the upper arm, the subclavian arteries continue as the axillary arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Elower limbs\u003C/strong\u003E are supplied by the femoral arteries, which are continuations of the external iliac arteries as they pass beneath the inguinal ligament.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Eabdomen\u003C/strong\u003E receives its blood supply from various branches of the abdominal aorta, including the celiac trunk, superior and inferior mesenteric arteries, and renal arteries.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Ehead\u003C/strong\u003E and \u003Cstrong\u003Eneck\u003C/strong\u003E are primarily supplied by the common carotid arteries, which branch into the internal and external carotid arteries to provide blood to the brain, face, and neck structures.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUnderstanding the major arterial supply to different body regions is crucial for clinical practice, especially in cases of vascular disease, trauma, or surgical interventions.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The subclavian arteries are the main blood vessels that supply the upper limbs.","The common carotid arteries supply blood to the head and neck, not the upper limbs.","Understanding the major arterial supply to different body regions is crucial for clinical practice."],"references":["Netter, F. H. Netter Atlas of Human Anatomy: Classic Regional Approach-Ebook. 2022. Elsevier Health Sciences","Rahimi O, Geiger Z. Anatomy, Thorax, Subclavian Arteries. [Updated 2023 Jul 24]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK539736/","Jacob, S. (2007). Human anatomy: a clinically-orientated approach. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemR